  "prompt": "How do I get Jimmy Wales to answer my question on Quora?",
  "response": "Getting Jimmy Wales, the co-founder of Wikipedia, to answer your question on Quora can be a bit of a challenge due to his busy schedule and the high volume of questions he likely receives. However, here are some strategies you can try to increase your chances:\n\n1. **Ask a Thoughtful and Relevant Question**:\n   - Ensure your question is well-phrased, clear, and directly relevant to Jimmy Wales' expertise or interests. Questions about Wikipedia, open-source knowledge, technology, or entrepreneurship are good starting points.\n\n2. **Tag Him Properly**:\n   - When posting your question on Quora, tag Jimmy Wales by typing \"@Jimmy Wales\" in the question details. This will notify him that he has been mentioned.\n\n3. **Choose the Right Topic Spaces**:\n   - Post your question in relevant Quora topic spaces that Jimmy Wales is likely to follow, such as \"Wikipedia,\" \"Technology,\" or \"Entrepreneurship.\"\n\n4. **Engage with His Content**:\n   - Follow Jimmy Wales on Quora and engage with his answers by upvoting or commenting thoughtfully. This may increase the likelihood that he notices your question.\n\n5. **Be Patient and Polite**:\n   - Recognize that Jimmy Wales may not have the time to answer every question. Being patient and respectful in your approach can make a positive impression.\n\n6. **Leverage Social Media**:\n   - If your question is particularly important, consider reaching out to Jimmy Wales on social media platforms like Twitter (X) or LinkedIn, where he is active. Politely ask if he would consider answering your question on Quora.\n\n7. **Network at Events**:\n   - If you have the opportunity to attend events where Jimmy Wales is speaking or participating, you could ask him your question directly or mention your Quora post in person.\n\nRemember, even with these strategies, there's no guarantee that he will respond. However, making your question as compelling and relevant as possible will maximize your chances!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
